<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Two-Letter Words Complete Strategy</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Scrabble Words Finder · Word of the Day</p>

    <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
      <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
      <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
      <span>9 min read</span>
    </div>

    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">Most players learn the 2-letter word list. Fewer players understand when and how to deploy them. Knowing that QI exists is one thing — knowing that placing it parallel to an existing word to form three scoring opportunities simultaneously is what separates casual players from club-level competitors.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Parallel Play Scoring — The Hidden Power</h2>

    <p>The single most valuable application of 2-letter words is parallel play. When you place a word alongside an existing word, every adjacent pair must form a valid 2-letter word. If they do, each pair scores independently.</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 How It Works</p>
      <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Place your word directly alongside an existing word so every <span class="text-white font-medium">vertical pair forms a valid 2-letter word</span>. You score your main word PLUS each crossword simultaneously — routinely 30-50 points from a "small" play.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The key constraint: every vertical pair must be valid. This is why knowing ALL 127 valid 2-letter words matters — even one invalid pair blocks the entire parallel play.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Complete Tier List</h2>

    <p>Not all 2-letter words are equal. Here's a tactical tier list based on frequency of use and scoring potential:</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
        <thead class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Tier</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Words</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Use Case</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
          <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-amber-500">Power</td><td class="px-4 py-3">QI, ZA, XI, XU, JO</td><td class="px-4 py-3">High-value tiles on premium squares</td></tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-blue-400">Utility</td><td class="px-4 py-3">RE, ER, EN, AN, IN, IT, IS, AT, TO</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Common parallel formations, hooks</td></tr>
          <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-purple-400">Vowel Dump</td><td class="px-4 py-3">AA, AE, AI, OE, OI, OU</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Shed excess vowels cheaply</td></tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-green-400">Consonant Dump</td><td class="px-4 py-3">SH, CH, MM, HM</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Shed heavy consonants</td></tr>
          <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-gray-400">Niche</td><td class="px-4 py-3">KA, KI, GI, FE, BI, BO</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Specific parallel situations only</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Vowel Dumps — When You're Drowning in Vowels</h2>

    <p>A rack like A-A-E-I-O-U-T is a nightmare — but you don't need to exchange. Strategic 2-letter vowel plays fix your rack while staying on the board:</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">AA</span> — Volcanic rock. Dumps two As at once. Worth 2 points on its own, 4 on DWS.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">AE</span> — One (Scottish). Sheds an A and an E in a single tile-efficient move.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">OI</span> — Interjection. Clears an O and an I, both common excess vowels.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">OU</span> — Man (Hawaiian). Removes the two vowels least useful for bingo stems.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✓ Key Principle</p>
      <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Even a 2-point play that sheds two bad vowels is <span class="text-white font-medium">better than exchanging</span>. When you exchange, you lose your turn entirely and gain no points. Playing AA on a DWS scores 4 points AND sheds 2 vowels AND possibly sets up a better play next turn.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Premium Square Targeting</h2>

    <p>Two-letter words shine brightest on premium squares because the multiplier applies to the full word even when it's just 2 tiles:</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
        <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">31 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">ZA on TLS</p></div>
        <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">27 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">XI on TWS</p></div>
        <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">XU on TLS</p></div>
        <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">21 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QI on DLS</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Power Tier + Premium:</span> QI on DLS gives 21 points. ZA on TLS gives 31 points. JO on DWS gives 18 points. These "tiny" plays outscore many 5-letter words.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Blocking and Defensive 2-Letter Plays</h2>

    <p>Two-letter words are your best defensive tool. They're small enough to fit into tight spaces and close off premium squares your opponent is targeting.</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Block TWS</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A 6-point play that blocks a potential 45-point play is a net 39-point swing in your favour.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Close Bingo Lanes</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A 2-letter word perpendicular to an open row breaks the 7-tile span needed for a bingo.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Deny Hooks</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Playing beside a hookable word removes the opponent's opportunity to extend it for big points.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Endgame Control</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">In final turns, 2-letter words let you score from nearly any position on a closed board.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Training Your Parallel Play Vision</h2>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Training Steps</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Memorise by column — learn which letters pair with each letter (A pairs with: A, B, D, E, G, H, I, L, M, N, R, S, T, W, X, Y)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Practice adjacency scanning — for every word on the board, mentally list what letters can go beside each letter</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Solve parallel puzzles — given a word on the board, what words can go parallel to it?</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Time yourself — in real games, give yourself 30 seconds to spot any parallel play before looking elsewhere</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

